==English==

===Etymology===
From {{ME.}} {{term|acord}}, {{term|accord#Middle English|accord}}, {{term|acorden}}, {{term|accorden}}, through {{OF.}} {{term|acort}}, {{term|acorde}}, and {{term|acorder}} (cf. modern French {{term|accord#French|accord}} and {{term|accorder}}), and in turn from {{LL.}} {{term|accordare#Latin|accordare}}, formed from {{L.}}  {{term|ad}} +  {{term|cordis||heart}}.

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-accord.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*{{rhymes|ɔː(r)d}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Agreement or [[concurrence]] of opinion, will, or action.
#*'''1769''', ''[[s:Bible_(King_James)|The King James Bible - Oxford Standard Text]]'',  [[s:Bible_(King_James)/Acts#Chapter_1|Acts 1:14]]
#*:These all continued with one '''accord''' in prayer.
# An [[harmony]] in sound, [[pitch]] and [[tone]]; [[concord]].
#*'''17th century''', "The Self-Subsistence of the Soul", [[w:John Davies (poet)|Sir John Davies]], 
#*:Those sweet '''accords''' are even the angels' lays.
# Agreement or harmony of things in general.
# {{law}} An agreement between parties in [[controversy]], by which satisfaction for an injury is [[stipulated]], and which, when [[executed]], prevents a lawsuit.

